
                        MKS Toolkit for DOS 
                        Release 4.1
			Manual Errata
                        October 30, 1992


PLEASE READ THIS DOCUMENT! It contains important, last minute information
that may not be present in the printed manuals.  

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
INSTALLATION MANUAL

- In several places the Installation Manual mentions that when a file
  is overwritten with a new file, the old version is saved with a .mks
  extension.  This behavior has been extended.  When another file with
  the same name is saved, the .mks file is saved with the .mk0 file extension.
  As subsequent files with this name are saved, the .mk0 extension changes
  to .mk1, then .mk2 through .mk9.

- Page 31 CONFIGURATION: Section 2.9 Configuration 5:

         $ROOTDIR is now removed from the lines:

         co;2;respawn;$ROOTDIR/bin/login.exe
         co;2;respawn;$ROOTDIR/bin/sh.exe

- Page 33 APPENDICES: Section 1.1.3 With Configuration 4:

         c:/ is now removed from the line:

         co;2;respawn; ENVSIZE=512 c:/bin/login.exe

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
USER'S GUIDE

- Page 65 Awk Tutorial: Introduction:

        The manual states that a book entitled The Awk Programming Language 
        is included in the MKS AWK package.  This book is not included with 
        MKS Toolkit.

- Page 96 AWK Tutorial: 5.2 The if Statement:

       An if statement is an action of the form 
                if (expression) statement1 else statement2

  Note: When the else statemant2 part of the if statement is on the same 
  line as the statement1, the else statement2 should be separated from the 
  statement1 by a semicolon (;).

- Page 97 AWK Tutorial: Please add:
  Remember that \t is the escape sequence for a tab character.

